  "prompt": "A triangle has angles in the ratio 2:3:4. What is the size of the smallest of the three angles?",
  "response": "In a triangle, the sum of the angles is always 180 degrees. Given the angles are in the ratio 2:3:4, let's denote the angles as \\(2x\\), \\(3x\\), and \\(4x\\).\n\nTo find \\(x\\), we set up the equation based on the sum of the angles:\n\n\\[ 2x + 3x + 4x = 180 \\]\n\\[ 9x = 180 \\]\n\\[ x = 20 \\]\n\nNow, we can determine the sizes of the angles:\n- The smallest angle is \\(2x = 2 \\times 20 = 40\\) degrees.\n\nTherefore, the size of the smallest angle is 40 degrees.",
